title: For Sale:  HOW TO SELL YOU PISTOL!
location: South Carolina, South Carolina, United States

As a gun collector, with professional experience ,here is some advice.
1.  Offer = Either has no clue the value of the pistol or most likely the are GOUGING people!
2. Rare = Usually is not!
3. Saw on Gun Broker = You are on Armslist! Gun Broker is for people who know little to nothing about firearms and get there wallets emptied and learn a hard lesson!
4. Free or &1.00 = This is illegal! Advertising at one price and charging a higher one is against Federal & State law. You are required to sell at the advertised price!!!
5. Best advice, research Armslist USA and see what your pistol is selling for on an AVERAGE!

title: For Sale:  Innovative Arms WAR upper complete
postcontent:
Brand new never installed. 

www.innovativearms.com

What the Warfighter will experience…
Turning to the suppressed mode from unsuppressed, you will immediately feel your rifle shooting smoother. The “blow back” in your face is almost non existent. No more burning eyes and choking gas. Your weapon has now become an average of 2 -2.5 DB quieter at the shooters ear with Innovative Arms silencers or other quality silencer brands. Your weapon will not only be shooting quieter but also cleaner. With less fouling and heat, the accelerated wear and tear that was once a standard issue is now a non-issue, giving your suppressed Black Rifle the longevity it deserves.

　

The W.A.R. is designed for the modern Warfighter and is to be fired only in conjunction with quality 5.56mm ammunition.

The Warfighter has two modes, SUPPRESSED/UNSUPPRESSED. By switching the lever in between modes the gas is "OFF" and results with the requirement to manually cycle the next round.
Innovative Arms has revolutionized the suppressor game with a new product named W.A.R. "Warfighter Adjustable Receiver patented, patent pending technology". The W.A.R. is in a class all by itself being the only upper reciever on the market with the ability to regulate gas flow at the upper reciever. There are big advantages in being able to make adjustments at this location over making the adjustment at the gas block.

Some may ask "why do I need to regulate gas flow when running a suppressor ?" Some of the benefits of regulating gas flow is that it reduces fouling, and blowback. By reducing blowback you reduce the action noise which makes the rifle quieter at the shooters ear. It also reduces the wear and tear from suppressor use. The W.A.R. does all this and more.

title: For Sale:  Weller soldering stations, brand new in box - Smoking deal!
location: Raleigh, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
Update: WES51 is sold. WESD51 still available.

I have two brand new in box Weller soldering stations. These are both temperature controlled soldering stations.

Weller WES51, $80

Weller WESD51, $120

Prices are firm.

The advantages of a temperature controlled (as opposed to wattage controlled) soldering station over a corded soldering iron:

-Variable temperature, and highly responsive current control
-Interchangable irons and tips
-Durability, you can replace the ceramic heating elements in the irons
-More power in a smaller package, the irons are smaller diameter and more comfortable than traditional irons
-Cooler in hand, because they use a small high power ceramic element out at the tip of the iron, the handle stays cooler during extended use

When using traditional corded irons, you have to keep several different wattage irons on hand for different size jobs. On top of that, you're stuck to a single temperature, and therefore a single type of solder. When you apply the iron to a part that sinks a lot of heat away, it cools the iron, and you have to wait for the iron to recover at its fixed wattage... all the while pumping unneccesary heat into your part.

With a soldering station, as soon as the electronics detect the iron cooling, they crank the current to recover the iron quickly... this means you bring your part up to temperature quickly, with as little excess heat as possible. All you need is a single iron and several tips, and you can safely and successfully solder anything from tiny IC's, to large battery terminals without worry of damaging your parts or cold solder joints.

postcontent:
Hey everyone, 
so I've decided to sell my 9mm Uzi. It is either an Israeli or German lower with select fire grip (made into only semi and tac welded so you cannot easily make it back full auto), collapsable folding stock, 32 round mag, and parts kit (semi auto) upper. I got this in trade and later was told that the barrel length it had made it require certain licensing. So, I removed/destroyed the other improper barrel, and this is now completely legal. It literally is ready to roll with the exception of the barrel itself.I was told by previous owner it shot great and had no issues, but have not shot myself as a result of discovering the status of the barrel. So, this will currently come without a barrel, so it leaves open to you whether you want to buy a short barrel and fill out the required paperwork, or buy the 16 inch or longer barrel and need no paperwork. Either way, the barrel itself will only run around 120ish (i already located some online). This has normal wear, dings, and scrapes you would expect any Uzi that wasn't a safe queen to have.This is still a great little gun and looks very authentic versus the remake ones that you see selling for 1400-2000 and are half plastic and spray paint looking. I am open to cash offers, trade offers for multiple guns, single guns, anything gun related really. Im very flexible on offers and I am reasonable on price. Thanks for looking 
JB

title: For Sale:  Russian Nagant Revolver
postcontent:
You are looking at 7.62x38 Russian Nagant Revolver model 1895, gas seal cylinder. This is a very interesting piece of history which is fully functional on the range! The only revolver that has cylinder move forward as you cock it to cover the gap and make a complete closure of the gap as you fire it. The only revolver that can actually be silenced. This model was created in 1895 for Russian Imperial Army and was used through WWI and WWII for Russian, Finnish, Bulgarian and many other armies of the world. 

This particular gun was made in 1944. It's in excellent shape and only has about 100 or so rounds through it. It's pretty accurate too, please refer to a target image on the bottom. Nagant is known for a pretty bad double action, however this one had a trigger job and double action is manageable. Of course it's not as good as on the new, contemporary revolver, but again: refer to a target image for results. If you need an ammo for this gun, I can point you to a reliable online resources where you can buy it.

The gun came to me new from the arsenal about a year ago, so you can say that I am the first owner. It comes with an original holster and cleaning rod. I can ship to a FFL for $35. Thanks.

An accessory FN FS2000® Tactical Fore-end is also available that provides three MIL -STD 1913 forward mounting rails.

title: For Sale:  Used Kel Tec PF-9
postcontent:
The PF-9 retains the best features from our P-11 and P-3AT pistols combined into the flattest and lightest single stack 9mm configuration ever made. The barrel, locking system, slide stop, assembly pin, front sight, recoil springs and guide rod are adapted from the P-11. The PF-9 is nearly identical to the P-11 in length and height and shares the same exterior controls. The shorter trigger system with integral hammer block and the extraction system are adapted from the P-3AT. Just like the P-11, the PF-9 will accept +P ammunition, however, not with continuous use.
     The rear sight is a new design and is adjustable for windage with the supplied allen wrench as well as for elevation with the use of shims (not included). The included 7 round rectangular magazine is supplied with a finger extension base plate and numbered holes. The under barrel accessory rail shares the dimensions of the MIL-STD-1913 picatinny rail although there is only one locking notch in the forward position.
